<font color="#FF0000">LOVE AND RESPECT</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar  4  1:01:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
love and respect:   Many of us knew what love was when we were children.  It was simple.  We associated it with mom and dad, grandma and grandpa the extended family.  It was safe and warm.  And we gave it to other people.  Sometimes they even expected it from us and it was easy to oblige.  As we got older we had to grow up and adjust our perspective.  We had to realize that our ocean of love was after all only a little pond.  There were more pervasive things to pay attention to.  Many of us Vietnam Vets found the experience of war so compelling that we identified the comraderie among ourselves with that original-primal love.  I cared for the welfare of my fellow soldiers as much as I cared for my own welfare.  We identified that as love.  I feel we were justified in that.  Such a love has been experienced by warriors down through the ages. As more mature individuals now we look for interior reservoirs of strength in order to cope with family, social and other challenges.  Does love fit in now and here?  Can we identify with something as strongly as we did back in Nam.  Something that will give us the strength to overcome ourselves and all other selves?  I think we all realize that such is not the way man is.  We would succumb to idealism on that course.  We can not save ourselves from ourselves.  Maybe there's a way.  Do you know of one?   
